Depyrimidination is a process in which the chemical bond linking a [[pyrimidine]] ([[Cytosine]] or [[Thymine]]) to a deoxyribose sugar breaks spontaneously. Depyrimidination occurs at a lower rate compared to [[depurination]] with only 500 cytosine and thymine bases lost per cell per day in a typical mammalian cell.
